  "prompt": "What does the \"@\" symbol mean in Objective-C?",
  "response": "In Objective-C, the \"@\" symbol has several uses:\n\n1. String Literals\n```objc\nNSString *str = @\"Hello World\";\n```\n\n2. Array Literals\n```objc\nNSArray *array = @[@1, @2, @3];\n```\n\n3. Dictionary Literals\n```objc\nNSDictionary *dict = @{@\"key1\": @\"value1\", @\"key2\": @\"value2\"};\n```\n\n4. Number Literals\n```objc\nNSNumber *num = @42;\nNSNumber *floatNum = @3.14;\nNSNumber *boolValue = @YES;\n```\n\n5. Boxed Expressions\n```objc\nNSNumber *intValue = @(10 + 5);\n```\n\n6. Selector Notation\n```objc\nSEL selector = @selector(methodName:);\n```\n\n7. Marking Enumeration Types\n```objc\ntypedef enum {\n    MyEnumValue1,\n    MyEnumValue2\n} MyEnum;\n```\n\n8. Marking Protocols\n```objc\n@protocol MyProtocol\n// Protocol methods\n@end\n```\n\n9. Marking Interface and Implementation\n```objc\n@interface MyClass : NSObject\n// Class declaration\n@end\n\n@implementation MyClass\n// Class implementation\n@end\n```\n\nThe \"@\" symbol is essentially a way to create compiler-recognized literals and provide syntactic sugar in Objective-C.",
